english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent Off to Choi the Registrar Upon His Return to Serve His Father
  author: Seo Sam-mun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My friend Choi, whose courtesy name is Ji-bo, is a man of integrity and conscientiousness. We came to know each other in the spring of the year gyeong-chuk. At that time, Choi's father was residing in the capital, and Choi was scrupulous in his morning and evening inquiries after his father's health. In attending to his father's needs, he seemed ever anxious, as though they were insufficient. I witnessed this with my own eyes as I came and went, and I could not help but feel that Choi surpassed me in filial devotion. From that time onward, our friendship grew ever deeper. Now that his father has retired to a villa in Yang-ji, I said to Choi, "Why do you not bring your father to your home and attend to his care there?" Choi replied with a sorrowful countenance, "My father feels at peace in that place. How can I presume to go against his wishes?" He then submitted his resignation to the court, gathered his wife and children, and departed southward. The former Director of the Office of Letters and Decorum, Master Choi, first composed a quatrain to celebrate his journey. I bow in reverence and humbly offer this preface.

    Our kingdom's successive sovereigns have inherited the throne through filial piety and governed through it. Whenever an official's parents dwell in distant places and grow old in years, the court grants them leave to return and provide care. Thus the parents receive the sustenance they deserve, and the children fulfill their sacred duty. The benevolence from above in thus honoring the elderly and cultivating filial piety is boundless and supreme.

    Yet whether a son returns to such care depends upon whether he can honor the virtue and righteousness of his parents' teachings and awaken the sincere reverence in his own heart. I have witnessed many scholars and officials who wear their caps proudly and carry themselves with measured dignity, whose faces show no trace of worry, appearing perfectly content. But when calamity strikes unexpectedly, they beat their chests and wail in bitter regret, only then lamenting that they failed to return and serve their parents in their latter years. How tragic that such remorse comes too late!

    When one's parents yet live, the opportunity for filial service awaits. Who forbade it? Who prevented it? Who detained you against your will? And now, what avails regret when the chance has passed?

    Does any person not know that returning to serve one's parents is beautiful, and failing to do so is shameful? Yet without prohibition they do not go; without hindrance they remain. This must be because their hearts are captivated by something else—the pursuit of office and rank.

    If a son could free himself from such attachment, he might truly be called filial, truly be called worthy. Otherwise, who would not regard Choi's departure as something beyond their reach? Who could deny that Choi's example awakens in me such reverence and admiration?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gyeong-chuk (계축) refers to a year in the Sexagenary cycle; historically this would be 1433.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'courtesy name' (字) was a secondary name given to scholars and officials in East Asia, typically used in formal or respectful contexts.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'four-line quatrain' (四韻詩) indicates a poem of four lines with end rhymes, a common poetic form.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Office of Letters and Decorum' (藝文館) was a prestigious governmental institution responsible for literature, rituals, and record-keeping.
